They depend on position and they also have components.

19
00:01:01,900 --> 00:01:08,300
They have direction, they have magnitude, and they depend on where you are.

20
00:01:08,300 --> 00:01:09,600
Electric field is one example.

21
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:12,600
Magnetic field is the one that we're really dealing with now.

22
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:16,800
And so we call it B.

23
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:19,900
We put a little arrow on top to indicate that it's a vector.

24
00:01:19,900 --> 00:01:22,200
And we say it's a function of position.

25
00:01:22,200 --> 00:01:25,300
We can also write it in terms of its components.

26
00:01:25,300 --> 00:01:26,800
Bi of x.

27
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:33,800
Or we can write that bi of x means bx, by, and bz.

28
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:35,800
All the same things.

29
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:37,800
All right, that's the magnetic field.

30
00:01:37,800 --> 00:01:40,400
They all depend on position.

31
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:42,000
There's a rule about magnetic fields.

32
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Where this rule comes from is not apparent at the moment.

33
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,800
It's a rule about magnetic fields that's partly an experimental rule,

34
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:55,900
partly also very consistent with our general theory.

35
00:01:55,900 --> 00:01:56,900
So, it's a rule about magnetic fields.

36
00:01:56,900 --> 00:02:00,100
Or generally theory of electromagnetism.

37
00:02:00,100 --> 00:02:03,200
It is a rule which may break down in the future.

38
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:06,900
It's the rule that there are no sources of the magnetic field.

39
00:02:06,900 --> 00:02:11,200
No analogs of charged particles for magnetic fields.

40
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:14,100
No magnetic monopoles.

41
00:02:14,100 --> 00:02:18,400
As I said, in the future, this may prove to be wrong.

42
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:24,300
But at least experimentally, and within the current framework of theory,

43
00:02:24,300 --> 00:02:25,500
it's true.

44
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:26,800
That the sources of magnetic fields are not magnetic fields.

45
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:29,000
The sources of the magnetic field are zero.

46
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
And that's the condition that del dot b is equal to zero.

47
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,400
If b was a flow of a fluid, it would be saying there are no sources of the fluid,

48
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:45,400
no pipe ends sticking out in space where water is flowing away in every direction.

49
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:48,500
All right, so del dot b equals zero.

50
00:02:48,500 --> 00:02:51,500
We can call that a constraint on a magnetic field.

51
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:54,600
Not any magnetic field is allowed.

52
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:56,000
Only some magnetic fields are allowed.

53
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:59,600
Those which satisfy del dot b equals zero.

54
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:02,700
Incidentally, one other thing for tonight in any case.

55
00:03:02,700 --> 00:03:05,500
This does not have to be the case in general.

56
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:10,600
But for our purposes tonight, let's assume that the magnetic field and electric field,

57
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:13,400
if it exists, are not dependent on time.

58
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:15,600
They don't vary.

59
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:17,400
Nothing big or different happens.

60
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:24,200
But just to be definite, time independent, static, electric, and magnetic fields.

61
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:24,800
All right, now.

62
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:30,900
We want to make sure that when we start thinking about magnetic fields,

63
00:03:30,900 --> 00:03:33,300
that we satisfy this condition here.

64
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:37,100
It would be nice if we could write it in an automatic way,

65
00:03:37,100 --> 00:03:46,900
where we didn't have to keep checking whether we are correctly implementing this condition.

66
00:03:46,900 --> 00:03:49,700
And one way of doing it, it's the accepted way of doing it,

67
00:03:49,700 --> 00:03:54,200
it's the effective way of doing it that works extremely well,

68
00:03:54,200 --> 00:03:56,600
is to say that the magnetic field,

69
00:03:56,800 --> 00:04:00,100
is the curl of something.

70
00:04:00,100 --> 00:04:04,500
That something is called the vect- oops, the vector potential.

71
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:10,500
And the reason that we do that is because

72
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:13,800
for any field A,

73
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:20,600
the divergence of a curl is always zero.

74
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:23,600
So, all we can say is, look,

75
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:26,600
we don't ever have to check or think about

76
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:29,800
whether the divergence of the magnetic field is zero,

77
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:37,300
if instead, we replace everywhere's B by del cross A.

78
00:04:37,300 --> 00:04:43,300
And that introduces the notion of a vector potential.

79
00:04:43,300 --> 00:04:45,100
It's automatic.

80
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:46,800
We don't have to think about it.

81
00:04:46,800 --> 00:04:51,200
However, it does introduce another element into things.

82
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:55,800
And the other element that it introduces is that the vector potential is not unique.

83
00:04:55,800 --> 00:05:01,000
If we start writing our equations in terms of the vector potential,

84
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:12,400
then different vector potentials will sometimes correspond to exactly the same physics.

85
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:14,100
And in fact, what's the condition?

86
00:05:14,100 --> 00:05:18,600
The condition is that two different vector potentials are the same

87
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:22,900
if they lead to the same magnetic field.

88
00:05:22,900 --> 00:05:25,600
What is the freedom in choosing,

89
00:05:25,600 --> 00:05:27,900
the vector potential?

90
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:30,900
Well,

91
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:34,300
now we use another fact about

92
00:05:34,300 --> 00:05:38,300
calculus or about vectors and scalar fields, about fields.

93
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:39,900
And it's the fact

94
00:05:39,900 --> 00:05:43,100
that the curl

95
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:45,800
of any gradient,

96
00:05:45,800 --> 00:05:49,600
the curl of any gradient

97
00:05:49,600 --> 00:05:53,300
del S

98
00:05:53,300 --> 00:05:55,400
is always equal to zero.

99
00:05:55,600 --> 00:06:02,000
So, that means

100
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,100
that if we add a gradient to A,

101
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:11,000
it will not change its curl.

102
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,700
That happens to be the only ambiguity.

103
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:15,500
It's possible to prove

104
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:17,900
that there's no other ambiguity

105
00:06:17,900 --> 00:06:19,400
in the vector potential

106
00:06:19,400 --> 00:06:22,400
other than adding to it

107
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:30,000
the gradient of a scalar.

108
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
That's the only ambiguity.

109
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
Any two vector potentials

110
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
which give rise to the same magnetic field,

111
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
the difference between them

112
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
will automatically be a gradient.

113
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
That's a mathematical theorem.

114
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
And so we can say that

115
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:54,000
