116
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:00,400
So, the vector potential is ambiguous up to a certain kind of transformation.

117
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:02,400
It's called a gauge transformation.

118
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:04,400
This is called a gauge transformation.

119
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:15,400
As I said, it represents an ambiguity in what the vector potential is.

120
00:07:15,400 --> 00:07:18,400
But what about the magnetic field?

121
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:22,400
What happens to the magnetic field when you make a gauge transformation?

122
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:23,400
And of course, the answer is nothing.

123
00:07:23,400 --> 00:07:26,000
That's the whole point.

124
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:30,800
And so one says that the magnetic field is gauge invariant.

125
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:36,400
In fact, anything that has real physical measurable significance

126
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:40,800
is gauge invariant.

127
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:44,000
We have an idea that the magnetic field,

128
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,100
as well as lots of other things

129
00:07:46,100 --> 00:07:49,000
that we might measure directly in the laboratory,

130
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:52,000
are gauge invariant.

131
00:07:53,400 --> 00:08:00,400
So, we do something a little bit odd.

132
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:02,400
We're going to talk about this more.

133
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:04,400
We do something a little bit odd.

