We're supposed to keep the endpoints fixed.

534
00:27:54,400 --> 00:27:56,400
We nail them down,

535
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:58,400
and we explore all trajectories

536
00:27:58,400 --> 00:28:00,400
and look for the ones which minimize...

537
00:28:00,400 --> 00:28:02,400
or look for the one which minimizes the action.

538
00:28:02,400 --> 00:28:05,400
If we keep the endpoints fixed,

539
00:28:05,400 --> 00:28:07,400
then when we vary the trajectory around,

540
00:28:07,400 --> 00:28:09,400
this doesn't change.

541
00:28:09,400 --> 00:28:11,400
And because it doesn't change,

542
00:28:11,400 --> 00:28:14,400
finding the minimum doesn't depend on it.

543
00:28:14,400 --> 00:28:18,400
So the answer is, although the action itself

544
00:28:18,400 --> 00:28:20,400
is not quite gauge invariant,

545
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:22,400
exploring the trajectories

546
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:25,400
keeping fixed the endpoints

547
00:28:25,400 --> 00:28:28,400
does give rise to a gauge invariant answer.

548
00:28:28,400 --> 00:28:31,400
The trajectory which minimizes the action

549
00:28:31,400 --> 00:28:33,400
will not depend on a gauge transformation

550
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:35,400
for this reason.

551
00:28:35,400 --> 00:28:37,400
All right, so we can be quite certain then.

552
00:28:37,400 --> 00:28:38,400
We don't have to check it.

553
00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:40,400
We're going to check it anyway.

554
00:28:40,400 --> 00:28:43,400
But we don't have to check that the equations of motion

555
00:28:43,400 --> 00:28:45,400
that follow from this Lagrangian

556
00:28:45,400 --> 00:28:47,400
will be gauge invariant.

557
00:28:47,400 --> 00:28:49,400
What does it mean to say they're gauge invariant?

558
00:28:49,400 --> 00:28:50,400
Yeah.

559
00:28:50,400 --> 00:28:52,400
What does it mean to say they're gauge invariant?

560
00:28:52,400 --> 00:28:54,400
It means when we work out the equations,

561
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:56,400
the vector potential is going to disappear,

562
00:28:56,400 --> 00:28:58,400
and what's going to be in its place?

563
00:28:58,400 --> 00:29:00,400
The magnetic field.

564
00:29:00,400 --> 00:29:02,400
In other words, the gauge,

565
00:29:02,400 --> 00:29:05,400
the vector potential is going to come in

566
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:09,400
in combinations which we'll recognize

567
00:29:09,400 --> 00:29:12,400
as components of the magnetic field.

568
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:13,400
Okay?

569
00:29:13,400 --> 00:29:15,400
All right, so let's do that.

570
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:17,400
Here's our Lagrangian.

571
00:29:22,400 --> 00:29:24,400
And I'm going to be really concrete

572
00:29:24,400 --> 00:29:26,400
and pedantic about it.

573
00:29:26,400 --> 00:29:28,400
What's the first thing we do

574
00:29:28,400 --> 00:29:30,400
when we encounter a Lagrangian

575
00:29:30,400 --> 00:29:32,400
and we want to work out the equations of motion?

576
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:34,400
Remember, the equations of motion,

577
00:29:34,400 --> 00:29:36,400
let's write them down.

578
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:38,400
They're p dot i,

579
00:29:38,400 --> 00:29:40,400
where p is what?

580
00:29:40,400 --> 00:29:42,400
p is the momentum,

581
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:46,400
is equal to partial of L

582
00:29:46,400 --> 00:29:49,400
with respect to xi.

583
00:29:49,400 --> 00:29:51,400
Those are the Lagrange equations of motion

584
00:29:51,400 --> 00:29:54,400
where, let me remind you what pi is,

585
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:59,400
pi is the partial derivative of the Lagrangian

586
00:29:59,400 --> 00:30:03,400
with respect to xi dot.

587
00:30:03,400 --> 00:30:06,400
In other words, pi is the derivative of the Lagrangian

588
00:30:06,400 --> 00:30:09,400
with respect to the velocity.

589
00:30:09,400 --> 00:30:16,400
Now, now I have to

590
00:30:16,400 --> 00:30:20,400
tell you more about the notion of momentum.

591
00:30:20,400 --> 00:30:21,400
There are two numbers.

592
00:30:21,400 --> 00:30:23,400
There are two notions of momentum.

593
00:30:23,400 --> 00:30:26,400
There are two distinct notions of momentum.

594
00:30:26,400 --> 00:30:29,400
One of them is just the old-fashioned momentum,

595
00:30:29,400 --> 00:30:31,400
mass times velocity.

596
00:30:31,400 --> 00:30:32,400
Okay?

597
00:30:32,400 --> 00:30:34,400
Mass times velocity.

598
00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:39,400
It's called the mechanical momentum.

599
00:30:39,400 --> 00:30:40,400
Where should we write it?

600
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:42,400
Okay, let's put it over here.

601
00:30:42,400 --> 00:30:49,400
mv equals mechanical momentum.

602
00:30:49,400 --> 00:30:50,400
That's also the definition

603
00:30:50,400 --> 00:30:53,400
that we encounter in elementary physics.

604
00:30:53,400 --> 00:30:56,400
Mass times velocity is momentum.

605
00:30:56,400 --> 00:30:58,400
Here's a different definition,

606
00:30:58,400 --> 00:31:01,400
namely, the derivative of the Lagrangian,

607
00:31:01,400 --> 00:31:03,400
sorry, the derivative of the Lagrangian

608
00:31:03,400 --> 00:31:05,400
with respect to the velocity,

609
00:31:05,400 --> 00:31:07,400
different definition,

610
00:31:07,400 --> 00:31:10,400
and it's called the canonical momentum.

611
00:31:10,400 --> 00:31:13,400
It's the momentum that you use

612
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:15,400
in Hamilton's equations.

613
00:31:15,400 --> 00:31:17,400
It's the momentum that you use

614
00:31:17,400 --> 00:31:20,400
throughout our formal,

615
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:22,400
construction,

616
00:31:22,400 --> 00:31:25,400
thing that goes into Poisson brackets,

617
00:31:25,400 --> 00:31:28,400
partial of L with respect to the velocity,

618
00:31:28,400 --> 00:31:29,400
derivative with respect to the velocity.

619
00:31:29,400 --> 00:31:30,400
Are they the same?

620
00:31:30,400 --> 00:31:33,400
Well, supposing there's only this term here,

621
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:36,400
and we differentiate L with respect to x dot,

622
00:31:36,400 --> 00:31:38,400
what do we get?

623
00:31:38,400 --> 00:31:39,400
We get mx dot.

624
00:31:39,400 --> 00:31:41,400
So yes, they're the same.

625
00:31:41,400 --> 00:31:44,400
Supposing this weren't here,

626
00:31:44,400 --> 00:31:46,400
but there was an ordinary potential energy,

627
00:31:46,400 --> 00:31:48,400
v of x, or u of x,

628
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:49,400
I forgot what we called it.

629
00:31:49,400 --> 00:31:51,400
Maybe we called it u of x.

630
00:31:51,400 --> 00:31:54,400
I'll call it u of x.

631
00:31:54,400 --> 00:31:57,400
A potential energy u of x.

632
00:31:57,400 --> 00:32:00,400
U of x doesn't depend on the velocities,

633
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:02,400
the velocity components,

634
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:05,400
so when you differentiate L with respect to x dot,

635
00:32:05,400 --> 00:32:07,400
this doesn't contribute.

636
00:32:07,400 --> 00:32:10,400
And it's still true that the canonical momentum

637
00:32:10,400 --> 00:32:13,400
and the mechanical momentum are the same thing.

638
00:32:13,400 --> 00:32:16,400
But with a magnetic field, or in general,

639
00:32:16,400 --> 00:32:18,400
in general, they're not the same thing.

640
00:32:19,400 --> 00:32:22,400
Let's see what we get.

641
00:32:22,400 --> 00:32:23,400
Here.

642
00:32:23,400 --> 00:32:24,400
What is p sub i?

643
00:32:24,400 --> 00:32:27,400
p sub i is partial of L with respect to,

644
00:32:27,400 --> 00:32:28,400
let's take the x component,

645
00:32:28,400 --> 00:32:31,400
let's not do i, just x, x dot.

646
00:32:31,400 --> 00:32:37,400
That's equal to mx dot,

647
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:40,400
but there's an extra term from here.

648
00:32:40,400 --> 00:32:46,400
Plus e over c, a sub x.

649
00:32:46,400 --> 00:32:48,400
That's it.

650
00:32:48,400 --> 00:32:50,400
That's the canonical momentum.

651
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:52,400
It is not equal to the mechanical momentum.

652
00:32:52,400 --> 00:32:55,400
They are two quite different things.

653
00:32:55,400 --> 00:32:57,400
When you're asking whether momentum is conserved

654
00:32:57,400 --> 00:33:00,400
by virtue of a symmetry,

655
00:33:00,400 --> 00:33:03,400
you're talking about this beast,

656
00:33:03,400 --> 00:33:05,400
not this one over here necessarily.

657
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:08,400
They might be the same, but they might not.

658
00:33:08,400 --> 00:33:10,400
Okay, so there we are.

659
00:33:10,400 --> 00:33:12,400
There's our p sub i.

660
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:17,400
And we want to work out the Lagrangian equation.

661
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:18,400
Here it is.

662
00:33:18,400 --> 00:33:25,400
p sub i dot is equal to partial of L with respect to x sub i.

663
00:33:25,400 --> 00:33:28,400
So let's work it out in detail.

664
00:33:28,400 --> 00:33:31,400
Okay, first of all, what is p sub i dot?

665
00:33:31,400 --> 00:33:34,400
It's just the time derivative of this.

666
00:33:34,400 --> 00:33:35,400
And what's that?

667
00:33:35,400 --> 00:33:39,400
That's m times the acceleration.

668
00:33:39,400 --> 00:33:40,400
That's good.

669
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:42,400
We got the acceleration, and that's where we want to go.

670
00:33:42,400 --> 00:33:44,400
We want to get some F equals m a formula.

671
00:33:44,400 --> 00:33:45,400
m times the acceleration,

672
00:33:45,400 --> 00:33:47,400
but then there's another term.

673
00:33:47,400 --> 00:33:53,400
e over c times the time derivative of a of x.

674
00:33:53,400 --> 00:33:57,400
Now, a of x is, of course, a function of position.

675
00:33:57,400 --> 00:33:59,400
It depends on where the particle is.

676
00:33:59,400 --> 00:34:01,400
The particle is moving around.

677
00:34:01,400 --> 00:34:04,400
The vector potential varies from place to place.

678
00:34:04,400 --> 00:34:07,400
And so at the position of the particle,

679
00:34:07,400 --> 00:34:09,400
the vector potential will vary with time,

680
00:34:09,400 --> 00:34:13,400
even though there may be no explicit dependence.

681
00:34:13,400 --> 00:34:16,400
The field may be completely constant

682
00:34:16,400 --> 00:34:18,400
at any given point,

683
00:34:18,400 --> 00:34:21,400
because the particle moves, a changes.

684
00:34:21,400 --> 00:34:24,400
So what's the change in a per unit time,

685
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:28,400
the derivative of a x with respect to time?

686
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:33,400
It's changing because the position is changing.

687
00:34:33,400 --> 00:34:34,400
So what do we get?

688
00:34:34,400 --> 00:34:42,400
We get derivative of a x with respect to x times x dot

689
00:34:42,400 --> 00:34:44,400
plus the derivative of a x with respect to y,

690
00:34:44,400 --> 00:34:49,400
times y dot,

691
00:34:49,400 --> 00:34:54,400
plus the derivative of a x with respect to z,

692
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:55,400
times z dot.

693
00:34:55,400 --> 00:34:57,400
What did I do?

694
00:34:57,400 --> 00:35:00,400
I just took this a x over here,

695
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:04,400
and I said it changes because the position of the particle changes.

696
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:08,400
It's x changes, it's y changes, and it's z change.

697
00:35:08,400 --> 00:35:11,400
This is the change in x and change in a,

698
00:35:11,400 --> 00:35:13,400
change in a x,

699
00:35:13,400 --> 00:35:16,400
because the particle moves.

700
00:35:16,400 --> 00:35:21,400
All right, that is the left-hand side of the equation.

701
00:35:21,400 --> 00:35:23,400
How about the right-hand side of the equation?

702
00:35:23,400 --> 00:35:25,400
We still have the right-hand side of the equation,

703
00:35:25,400 --> 00:35:29,400
so let's go to the right-hand side of the equation.

704
00:35:29,400 --> 00:35:32,400
That is the derivative of L, in this case,

705
00:35:32,400 --> 00:35:35,400
let's say p sub x,

706
00:35:35,400 --> 00:35:40,400
the derivative of the Lagrangian with respect to x.

707
00:35:40,400 --> 00:35:42,400
This term here doesn't depend on x at all.

708
00:35:42,400 --> 00:35:45,400
It only depends on velocities.

709
00:35:45,400 --> 00:35:48,400
How about this term? Does this term depend on x?

710
00:35:48,400 --> 00:35:51,400
Well, sure it does. a depends on x.

711
00:35:51,400 --> 00:35:54,400
So, we get on the right-hand side,

712
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:57,400
e over c,

713
00:35:57,400 --> 00:36:01,400
times the derivative of a x with respect to x,

714
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:04,400
times x dot.

715
00:36:04,400 --> 00:36:06,400
Then there's a term from here,

716
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:09,400
plus partial of a y with respect to x,

717
00:36:09,400 --> 00:36:11,400
times y dot,

718
00:36:11,400 --> 00:36:15,400
plus partial of a z with respect to x,

719
00:36:15,400 --> 00:36:18,400
times z dot.

720
00:36:18,400 --> 00:36:27,400
All I've done was differentiate each one of these with respect to x.

721
00:36:27,400 --> 00:36:30,400
Sorry, I'm in the wrong place, aren't I?

722
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:36,400
The equals should go here.

723
00:36:36,400 --> 00:36:39,400
It's the right-hand side of this equation.

724
00:36:39,400 --> 00:36:40,400
All right, so let's go to the right-hand side of this equation.

725
00:36:41,400 --> 00:36:43,400
Let's bring it down where it belongs.

726
00:37:11,400 --> 00:37:15,400
The thing in this bracket over here

727
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:18,400
looks a little bit like the thing in this bracket over here,

728
00:37:18,400 --> 00:37:21,400
but they're actually quite different if you look at them.

729
00:37:21,400 --> 00:37:24,400
The first term is the same.

730
00:37:24,400 --> 00:37:27,400
Derivative of a x with respect to x times x dot.

731
00:37:27,400 --> 00:37:29,400
Same thing over here.

732
00:37:29,400 --> 00:37:31,400
Any questions about this? I don't want to go too fast.

733
00:37:31,400 --> 00:37:32,400
Yeah?

734
00:37:32,400 --> 00:37:38,400
In the Lagrangian, is the second term a kinetic energy or a potential energy?

735
00:37:41,400 --> 00:37:45,400
That's a word.

736
00:37:45,400 --> 00:37:46,400
It's neither.

737
00:37:46,400 --> 00:37:49,400
So how do you know whether to add it or subtract it?

738
00:37:49,400 --> 00:37:52,400
Oh, I'm saying let's try it out.

739
00:37:52,400 --> 00:37:55,400
Let's just try it out.

740
00:37:55,400 --> 00:37:57,400
We could try it out subtracting it, too.

741
00:37:57,400 --> 00:37:59,400
We can try it out both ways.

742
00:37:59,400 --> 00:38:01,400
We can try it out both ways.

743
00:38:01,400 --> 00:38:04,400
We could try all kinds of things.

744
00:38:04,400 --> 00:38:08,400
I'm short-cutting a bit of the work for you

745
00:38:08,400 --> 00:38:10,400
and telling you what the answer is,

746
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:12,400
and now we're going to check the answer.

747
00:38:12,400 --> 00:38:19,400
But subtracting it would only correspond to changing the sign of a.

748
00:38:19,400 --> 00:38:21,400
So we just go a to minus a.

749
00:38:21,400 --> 00:38:22,400
Replace a by minus a.

750
00:38:22,400 --> 00:38:24,400
The formulas would be the same,

751
00:38:24,400 --> 00:38:26,400
except wherever you would see an a, you would stick a minus a.

752
00:38:26,400 --> 00:38:31,400
So it wouldn't make much difference.

753
00:38:31,400 --> 00:38:36,400
All right, so here we are.

754
00:38:36,400 --> 00:38:39,400
And at this level, we might,

755
00:38:39,400 --> 00:38:40,400
at least,

756
00:38:40,400 --> 00:38:43,400
as well never have heard of a magnetic field.

757
00:38:43,400 --> 00:38:46,400
We've written down some equations of motion.

758
00:38:46,400 --> 00:38:48,400
We never heard of a magnetic field.

759
00:38:48,400 --> 00:38:52,400
Let's just follow our noses with this equation

760
00:38:52,400 --> 00:38:54,400
and see what we get,

761
00:38:54,400 --> 00:38:57,400
pretending we had never heard of the concept of a magnetic field.

762
00:38:57,400 --> 00:38:59,400
That last term should be ax.

763
00:38:59,400 --> 00:39:01,400
Yes, you're right. Thank you.

764
00:39:01,400 --> 00:39:02,400
No, it's az.

765
00:39:02,400 --> 00:39:04,400
Ax, ay, az.

766
00:39:04,400 --> 00:39:06,400
The middle one is y.

767
00:39:06,400 --> 00:39:08,400
Yeah, middle one is y. Good.

768
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:09,400
Yeah, okay.

769
00:39:09,400 --> 00:39:11,400
So you're at the top.

770
00:39:11,400 --> 00:39:13,400
You're differentiating this with respect to x,

771
00:39:13,400 --> 00:39:14,400
this with respect to x,

772
00:39:14,400 --> 00:39:16,400
and this with respect to x.

773
00:39:16,400 --> 00:39:17,400
Okay?

774
00:39:17,400 --> 00:39:24,400
On the other hand, the term in the left only has ax's.

775
00:39:24,400 --> 00:39:27,400
It only has ax's on the left,

776
00:39:27,400 --> 00:39:34,400
and that's because it comes from calculating the time derivative of ax here.

777
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:36,400
See, they come from different places.

778
00:39:36,400 --> 00:39:38,400
On the right-hand side,

779
00:39:38,400 --> 00:39:42,400
you're getting something that comes from differentiating with respect to x.

780
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:44,400
So you get three different terms.

781
00:39:44,400 --> 00:39:46,400
Derivative of ax with respect to x,

782
00:39:46,400 --> 00:39:47,400
derivative of ay with respect to x,

783
00:39:47,400 --> 00:39:50,400
derivative of az with respect to x.

784
00:39:50,400 --> 00:39:53,400
On the other hand, on the other side of the equation,

785
00:39:53,400 --> 00:39:56,400
you're differentiating p sub x with respect to time.

786
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:58,400
So it's always ax,

787
00:39:58,400 --> 00:40:03,400
but different velocity components there.

788
00:40:03,400 --> 00:40:05,400
Okay, that's the setup,

789
00:40:05,400 --> 00:40:07,400
and now let's see what cancels and what doesn't cancel,

790
00:40:07,400 --> 00:40:08,400
and manipulate it,

791
00:40:08,400 --> 00:40:10,400
and see what kind of things we get.

792
00:40:10,400 --> 00:40:14,400
First of all, the left-hand side contains m,

793
00:40:14,400 --> 00:40:17,400
and just the a component of the acceleration.

794
00:40:17,400 --> 00:40:20,400
Let's call it by a familiar name,

795
00:40:20,400 --> 00:40:24,400
the x component of acceleration.

796
00:40:24,400 --> 00:40:28,400
Next, certain terms cancel.

797
00:40:28,400 --> 00:40:30,400
Let's cancel the ones that cancel.

798
00:40:30,400 --> 00:40:33,400
ax with respect to x times x dot,

799
00:40:33,400 --> 00:40:35,400
same thing over here.

800
00:40:35,400 --> 00:40:36,400
So let's...

801
00:40:37,400 --> 00:40:39,400
I don't want to erase them.

802
00:40:39,400 --> 00:40:44,400
I just want to block them out.

